Analysing a proteomics data set using lgpr¶

Here we analyse one protein from a published longitudinal proteomics data set (Liu et al., 2018).

1. Data loading¶

The code below loads and visualizes the data.

In [2]:
readLiuData <- function(dataDir, protein){
  fn_X   <- paste(dataDir,"/liu_preproc_X.csv",sep="")
  fn_Y   <- paste(dataDir,"/liu_preproc_Y.csv",sep="")
  X_data <- read.csv(fn_X, header=TRUE, sep=",")
  X_data <- X_data[,1:5]
  Y_data <- read.csv(fn_Y, header=TRUE, sep=",")
  names  <- colnames(Y_data)
  if(!is.character(protein)){
    pname <- names[protein]
  }else{
    pname <- protein
  }
  
  cat("Read data for protein '", pname, "'. \n", sep = "")
  y      <- Y_data[[pname]]
  notnan <- which(!is.nan(y))
  n_nan  <- length(which(is.nan(y)))
  data   <- data.frame(cbind(X_data, y))
  data   <- data[notnan, ]
  cat("Removed ", n_nan , " rows with NaN value for the response variable.\n", sep = "")
  return(data)
}


FONT_SIZE <- 18

2. Homogeneous disease effect modeling¶

We first fit a model where the possible disease effect has to be identical for all diagnosed individuals.

In [3]:
CNTR     <- list(adapt_delta = 0.95) # set the adapt_delta parameter for dynamic HMC sampling
my_prior <- prior_default()

fit1 <- lgp(formula      = y ~ id + age + diseaseAge + sex + group,
            data         = data,
            prior        = my_prior,
            offset_vars  = "group",
            control      = CNTR,
            iter         = 2000,
            equal_effect = TRUE,
            chains       = 4,
            parallel     = TRUE,
            save_warmup  = FALSE,
            refresh      = 0,
            verbose      = TRUE)

3. Heterogeneous disease effect modeling¶

Next we fit a model where the magnitude of a possible disease effect can vary over diagnosed individuals (this will take longer to run).

As we see, the relevance of the diseaseAge covariate is now higher than for the homogeneous model. Visualization of inferred effects reveals that only part of the individuals experience a strong disease effect near the time of seroconversion.

4. Component selection methods¶

To further assess the component relevances for the heterogeneous model, we first we plot the distribution of component relevances over all posterior samples.

In [19]:
options(repr.plot.width=12, repr.plot.height=8) 
plot(fit2) + theme(text=element_text(size=FONT_SIZE))

We can plot the selection probabilities as a function of the threshold.

In [29]:
pfun <- function(x){stats::dbeta(x, 100, 5)}
sel <- selection_prob(fit2, p = pfun, h = 0.001)
options(repr.plot.width=11, repr.plot.height=6)
sel$plot + theme(text=element_text(size=FONT_SIZE))

For example, using the threshold $\tau = 0.95$, the selection probabilities are

In [30]:
lgpr:::selection_prob_fixed_threshold(fit2, 0.95)
f[(1)](id, age)
1
f[(2)](age)
0.13625
f[(3)](diseaseAge)
1
f[(4)](sex, age)
5e-04
f[(5)](group)
0

To avoid having to fix a specific threshold value, we can give a distribution $p(\tau)$ to weigh different threshold values. The selection probability for component $j$ is then obtained as $$ p_j = \int_0^1 p(\tau)p_j(\tau) d\tau, $$ where $p_j(\tau)$ is the selection probability of component $j$ using fixed threshold $\tau$. Here we used the $Beta(100,5)$ distribution to weight thresholds. This distribution and the weighted selection probabilities are shown below.

In [34]:
x <- seq(0,1,length.out=500)
f <- pfun(x)
plot(x,f,'l',col='firebrick3',main='Beta(100,5)')
print(round(sel$prob, 3))
